  "text": "Firefox crashes when processing CSS calc() expressions with extreme values (infinity, negative infinity, and NaN). The issue spans both the Servo CSS engine (Rust) and Gecko's C++ FFI layer.\n\n## Parsing (Servo Side)\nThe parsing of CSS calc() expressions occurs in **servo/components/style/values/specified/calc.rs**. The `CalcNode::parse_one()` function at line 610 parses calc expressions including special numeric constants. At lines 681-683, the parser allows infinity and NaN values:\n```rust\n\"infinity\" => Leaf::Number(f32::INFINITY),\n\"-infinity\" => Leaf::Number(f32::NEG_INFINITY),\n\"nan\" => Leaf::Number(f32::NAN),\n```\n\n## Numeric Overflow During Resolution\nThe actual calculation and overflow handling occurs in **servo/components/style/values/generics/calc.rs** in the `CalcNode::resolve_internal()` function. This function evaluates calc expressions recursively. Critical arithmetic operations happen at:\n- Sum operations (line 950): `left + right` can overflow\n- Product operations (lines 965, 971): `v * left` and `v * right` can produce infinity\n- Min/Max operations (lines 1005-1006): Comparisons with infinity values\n- Clamp operations (lines 1038-1042): Clamping with infinity edge cases\n\n## Length-Percentage Computation\nFor length-percentage values, **servo/components/style/values/computed/length_percentage.rs** contains the `CalcLengthPercentage::resolve()` function (line 991) which resolves percentages by multiplying with a basis:\n```rust\nCalcLengthPercentageLeaf::Length(Length::new(basis.px() * p.0))\n```\nWhen `basis.px()` or `p.0` is infinity, this multiplication can produce infinity. The resolved value is then clamped at line 1004:\n```rust\nLength::new(self.clamping_mode.clamp(px.px())).normalized()\n```\n\nThe `CalcLengthPercentageLeaf::try_sum_in_place()` (line 796) and `try_product_in_place()` (line 834) methods perform in-place arithmetic that can produce infinity values without proper validation.\n\n## Clamping Logic\nIn **servo/components/style_traits/values.rs**, the `AllowedNumericType::clamp()` function (line 593) attempts to clamp values:\n```rust\npub fn clamp(&self, val: f32) -> f32 {\n    match *self {\n        AllowedNumericType::All => val,\n        AllowedNumericType::NonNegative => val.max(0.),\n        AllowedNumericType::AtLeastOne => val.max(1.),\n        AllowedNumericType::ZeroToOne => val.max(0.).min(1.),\n    }\n}\n```\nFor infinity values with `AllowedNumericType::NonNegative`, `val.max(0.)` returns infinity unchanged.\n\n## Normalization\nIn **servo/components/style/values/computed/length.rs**, the `CSSPixelLength::normalized()` function (line 237) only handles NaN:\n```rust\npub fn normalized(self) -> Self {\n    Self::new(crate::values::normalize(self.0))\n}\n```\nThe `normalize()` function in **servo/components/style/values/mod.rs** converts NaN to 0.0 but does not handle infinity, allowing infinity values to propagate.\n\n## Gecko FFI Layer\nThe C++ Gecko code calls into Servo via the FFI function `Servo_ResolveCalcLengthPercentage()`. In **layout/style/ServoStyleConstsInlines.h**, the `StyleCalcLengthPercentage::ResolveToCSSPixels()` function (line 726) and `StyleCalcLengthPercentage::Resolve()` function (line 731) invoke the Servo resolution, which can return infinity values that Gecko does not properly handle, potentially causing crashes."
}

